We note that as $c \rightarrow {\infty}$ for fixed ${{\vec Q}}'$, the factor in $(\cdots)$ becomes unity, and the correction ${{\vec V}}'$ becomes independent of ${\bf H}$.  Thus in this limit the only part of ${\bf H}$ that influences  the full ${{\vec V}}$ is the equipotential part: ${\bf H} {\vec u}$.  

\section{Electrostatic energy}
\label{sec:energy}

Given this expression for the potential vector ${{\vec V}}$, we may find the electrostatic energy ${\cal E}$ for a given charge vector ${{\vec Q}}$: ${\cal E} = {\frac{1}{2}} \sum_i Q_i V_i = {\frac{1}{2}} {{\vec Q}} \cdot {{\vec V}}$.  In terms of the charge difference ${{\vec Q}}' {\equiv} {{\vec Q}} - {{\vec Q}}_e$ and potentials ${{\vec V}}'$, ${\cal E}$ can be written using Eq.~(\ref{eq:V'Q'2})

text:
\begin{equation}
{\cal E} = {\frac{1}{2}} ({{\vec Q}}_e + {{\vec Q}}')\cdot (V_e {\vec u} + {{\vec V}}')
= {\frac{1}{2}} Q V_e  + {\frac{1}{2}}  V_e~{{\vec Q}}' \cdot {\vec u} + {\frac{1}{2}} {{\vec Q}}_e \cdot {{\vec V}}'  + {\frac{1}{2}} {{\vec Q}}'\cdot {{\vec V}}' .
\label{eq:calEbig}
\end{equation}

\begin{equation}
{\cal E} = {\cal E}_e   + {\frac{1}{2}} {{\vec Q}}' \cdot {{\vec V}}'
= {\cal E}_e   +  {\frac{1}{2}} ~\frac 1 {c(h)} {{\vec Q}}' \cdot  \left ( {\bf 1} + \frac 1 {c(h)}\tilde{\bf L}^{-1}{\bf H}\right )^{-1}\tilde{\bf L}^{-1} {{\vec Q}}'  . 
\label{eq:calEfull}
\end{equation}

nexttext:
Using $({\underline{{\vec k}}} \cdot {{\vec Q}})^2 {\sim} 1/n$ and $L {\sim} n^{1/3}$, we conclude ${\cal E}' {\sim} n^0$.  

We now consider the effect of the ${{\vec Q}}_e$ part of ${{\vec Q}}'$.  For both clusters ${{\vec Q}}_e$ is concentrated at the outer boundary.  It thus has significant Fourier components at large $k$.  However, this charge concentration is in any case qualitatively weaker than the complete concentration found in ${{\vec Q}}$.  Accordingly we expect the ${{\vec Q}}_e$ part of ${{\vec Q}}'$ to have a minor effect and the scaling estimates for ${\cal E}'$ to hold for the full ${{\vec Q}}'$ as for the ${{\vec Q}}$.  

The foregoing estimates indicate a qualitative difference in ${\cal E}'$ in the two cases.  This positive energy diverges with $n$ for the extended cluster but remains finite for the compact cluster.  It disfavors the extended cluster.  This contrasts with the equipotential part of ${\cal E}$, which favors extended clusters.  This equipotential energy ${\cal E}_e$ is of order $\log n/n$ for extended clusters and of order $1/L {\sim} n^{-1/3} $ for compact clusters.  The total energy ${\cal E} = {\cal E}_e + {\cal E}'$ thus favors compact clusters, in contrast to the ``leading" ${\cal E}_e$ alone.









